{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_K6vDvHCjPbnWFda71oX58rDo","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\ttitle: Files dispatch\n3\tmodel: M\n4\tfunctions: []\n5\tcanDelegateTo:\n6\t  - system-files/reader\n7\t  - system-files/sheet\n8\t  - system-vision/vision\n9\t---\n10\t\n11\t# Route the attached file(s) to the right reader\n12\t\n13\tYou have been delegated a request about one or more attached FILES. Your message\n14\tlists each attachment as a note of the form:\n15\t\n16\t```\n17\t[Attached file id=\"<id>\" type=\"<mediaType>\" name=\"<filename>\" — call `await readDocument(\"<id>\")` to read it.]\n18\t```\n19\t\n20\tYou do NOT read the files yourself. You look at each attachment's **mediaType/filename**\n21\tand split the ids into two groups:\n22\t\n23\t- **Tabular** — `text/csv`, `application/vnd.ms-excel`, any `spreadsheet`/`xlsx`/`xls`/\n24\t  `ods`/`tsv` type or extension → the `sheet` specialist.\n25\t- **Everything else** — PDF (`application/pdf`), Word (`docx`), PowerPoint (`pptx`),\n26\t  OpenDocument text/presentation (`odt`/`odp`), plain text (`text/*`), Markdown, JSON,\n27\t  code, etc. → the `reader` specialist.\n28\t\n29\tThen delegate **once per group**, passing that group's FULL list of ids (each specialist\n30\treads many files in one shot). Delegate the two groups in parallel when both are present:\n31\t\n32\t```ts\n33\t// Example: two documents + one spreadsheet were attached.\n34\tconst [docAnswer, sheetAnswer] = await Promise.all([\n35\t  delegate('system-files', 'reader', {\n36\t    query: '<the user\\'s question, or \"\" if none>',\n37\t    attachmentIds: ['<pdf-id>', '<docx-id>'],\n38\t  }),\n39\t  delegate('system-files', 'sheet', {\n40\t    query: '<the same question>',\n41\t    attachmentIds: ['<xlsx-id>'],\n42\t  }),\n43\t]);\n44\t```\n45\t\n46\tThen resolve with the specialist answer(s):\n47\t\n48\t```ts\n49\t// One group → resolve its answer verbatim. Both groups → combine them plainly.\n50\tcurrentTask.resolve(\n51\t  [docAnswer, sheetAnswer].filter(Boolean).join('\\n\\n'),\n52\t);\n53\t```\n54\t\n55\tIf only one group has files, delegate just that one and resolve its answer directly.\n56\t\n57\t## A document with no text is a PICTURE of a document — look at it\n58\t\n59\tSome documents carry no extractable text at all: they are **scans**, i.e. photographs of\n60\tpaper. The reader cannot read those, and it will tell you so in words that name the\n61\t**page image ids** the host produced for them. That is not a failure to report to the\n62\tuser — it is a second hop to take:\n63\t\n64\t```ts\n65\t// The reader came back saying a file had no text and named its page image id(s).\n66\tconst seen = await delegate('system-vision', 'vision', {\n67\t  query: '<the same question, or \"describe/transcribe everything on this page\">',\n68\t  attachmentIds: ['<page-image-id>'],\n69\t});\n70\t```\n71\t\n72\tThen resolve with the vision answer folded in, attributed to that file. **Never** hand\n73\tback \"this file could not be read\" while a way to read it exists, and never guess what a\n74\tdocument says from its name — a page you have not looked at is not a page you know.\n75\t\n76\tGuidelines:\n77\t\n78\t- Pass every attachment id through unchanged — the specialists re-read each file via\n79\t  `readDocument(id)`; do not try to read or summarize anything here.\n80\t- Group by type: send all tabular ids to `sheet` and all other ids to `reader`. Never\n81\t  send a spreadsheet to `reader` or a document to `sheet`.\n82\t- If a type is genuinely unsupported, resolve with a short note saying so. An IMAGE is\n83\t  not unsupported: send it (and any page image of a scan) to the vision analyst.\n84\t- Resolve with the specialist answer(s) as-is (they are handed back to relay to the\n85\t  user) — do not re-summarize or embellish.\n86\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cfe78b6a-97f2-4499-9269-8aedfbe3c777","uuid":"891a39b7-39ba-4229-8b7e-e5b8ee1f2793","timestamp":"2026-07-15T20:50:28.601Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-files/agents/dispatch/instruct.md","content":"---\ntitle: Files dispatch\nmodel: M\nfunctions: []\ncanDelegateTo:\n  - system-files/reader\n  - system-files/sheet\n  - system-vision/vision\n---\n\n# Route the attached file(s) to the right reader\n\nYou have been delegated a request about one or more attached FILES. Your message\nlists each attachment as a note of the form:\n\n```\n[Attached file id=\"<id>\" type=\"<mediaType>\" name=\"<filename>\" — call `await readDocument(\"<id>\")` to read it.]\n```\n\nYou do NOT read the files yourself. You look at each attachment's **mediaType/filename**\nand split the ids into two groups:\n\n- **Tabular** — `text/csv`, `application/vnd.ms-excel`, any `spreadsheet`/`xlsx`/`xls`/\n  `ods`/`tsv` type or extension → the `sheet` specialist.\n- **Everything else** — PDF (`application/pdf`), Word (`docx`), PowerPoint (`pptx`),\n  OpenDocument text/presentation (`odt`/`odp`), plain text (`text/*`), Markdown, JSON,\n  code, etc. → the `reader` specialist.\n\nThen delegate **once per group**, passing that group's FULL list of ids (each specialist\nreads many files in one shot). Delegate the two groups in parallel when both are present:\n\n```ts\n// Example: two documents + one spreadsheet were attached.\nconst [docAnswer, sheetAnswer] = await Promise.all([\n  delegate('system-files', 'reader', {\n    query: '<the user\\'s question, or \"\" if none>',\n    attachmentIds: ['<pdf-id>', '<docx-id>'],\n  }),\n  delegate('system-files', 'sheet', {\n    query: '<the same question>',\n    attachmentIds: ['<xlsx-id>'],\n  }),\n]);\n```\n\nThen resolve with the specialist answer(s):\n\n```ts\n// One group → resolve its answer verbatim. Both groups → combine them plainly.\ncurrentTask.resolve(\n  [docAnswer, sheetAnswer].filter(Boolean).join('\\n\\n'),\n);\n```\n\nIf only one group has files, delegate just that one and resolve its answer directly.\n\n## A document with no text is a PICTURE of a document — look at it\n\nSome documents carry no extractable text at all: they are **scans**, i.e. photographs of\npaper. The reader cannot read those, and it will tell you so in words that name the\n**page image ids** the host produced for them. That is not a failure to report to the\nuser — it is a second hop to take:\n\n```ts\n// The reader came back saying a file had no text and named its page image id(s).\nconst seen = await delegate('system-vision', 'vision', {\n  query: '<the same question, or \"describe/transcribe everything on this page\">',\n  attachmentIds: ['<page-image-id>'],\n});\n```\n\nThen resolve with the vision answer folded in, attributed to that file. **Never** hand\nback \"this file could not be read\" while a way to read it exists, and never guess what a\ndocument says from its name — a page you have not looked at is not a page you know.\n\nGuidelines:\n\n- Pass every attachment id through unchanged — the specialists re-read each file via\n  `readDocument(id)`; do not try to read or summarize anything here.\n- Group by type: send all tabular ids to `sheet` and all other ids to `reader`. Never\n  send a spreadsheet to `reader` or a document to `sheet`.\n- If a type is genuinely unsupported, resolve with a short note saying so. An IMAGE is\n  not unsupported: send it (and any page image of a scan) to the vision analyst.\n- Resolve with the specialist answer(s) as-is (they are handed back to relay to the\n  user) — do not re-summarize or embellish.\n","numLines":86,"startLine":1,"totalLines":86}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_EtOFz4cCKnW1zJhMttbtbQ6H","type":"tool_result","content":"60\tCall it once — not every turn — and don't ask the user for a name:\n61\t\n62\t```typescript\n63\tawait setSessionMeta({ title: 'Bolognese from scratch', slug: 'bolognese-from-scratch' });\n64\t```\n65\t\n66\tThe host slugifies `slug` (lowercased, non-alphanumerics → `-`); either field is optional.\n67\t\n68\t## Attachments — you cannot see images/files yourself\n69\t\n70\tYou are a text model: you CANNOT read an attached image or file directly. When your\n71\tmessage lists attachments (each with an `attachmentId`), delegate to the right\n72\tspecialist and pass the id(s), then use the returned text to answer the user. Send ALL\n73\timage ids in ONE vision delegation and ALL file ids in ONE files delegation (the\n74\tspecialists read many at once) — don't delegate the same kind once per file. Run the\n75\tindependent delegations together with `Promise.all`; `delegate()` already returns a\n76\t`Promise`, so do not cast either call inside the array:\n77\t\n78\t```typescript\n79\tconst [seen, fileAnswer] = await Promise.all([\n80\t  // images → the vision analyst (runs on a vision model); pass every image id\n81\t  delegate('system-vision', 'vision', {\n82\t    query: 'What is in these pictures?',\n83\t    attachmentIds: ['<image-id-1>', '<image-id-2>'],\n84\t  }),\n85\t  // files → the files dispatcher (routes PDFs/docs to the reader, CSV/XLSX/ODS to the\n86\t  // sheet analyst; it handles a mixed batch); pass every file id\n87\t  delegate('system-files', 'dispatch', {\n88\t    query: 'Summarize these documents',\n89\t    attachmentIds: ['<file-id-1>', '<file-id-2>'],\n90\t  }),\n91\t]);\n92\t// SPEAK IN THE SAME STATEMENT. What comes back is FOR YOU — write the user's reply out of it, HERE,\n93\t// while you still hold it. Do NOT display the raw value (see \"Never show them your plumbing\"), and\n94\t// do NOT put off the reply to a later statement: your variables DO NOT PERSIST between statements,\n95\t// so `seen` and `fileAnswer` are gone by the next one and you will be left with\n96\t// `Cannot find name 'seen'`, re-reading files you already read.\n97\tdisplay(\n98\t  <Stack gap={2}>\n99\t    <Paragraph>{/* what you LEARNED from the pictures — in their words, not the model's */}</Paragraph>\n100\t    <Paragraph>{/* what you LEARNED from the documents — the specifics they would recognise */}</Paragraph>\n101\t  </Stack>,\n102\t);\n103\t```\n104\t\n105\tAudio attachments are already transcribed to text in your message — just read and\n106\tanswer them yourself (no delegation). Delegate images/files, integrate the result,\n107\tthen reply. This takes priority over the triage paths below when attachments are present.\n108\t\n109\t**Read to ORIENT, not to COPY.** Ask the specialist for a SHORT summary plus the handful of\n110\tconcrete specifics you need to speak credibly about the material (\"summarize these, and list the\n111\tkey names, dates and figures\"). Do NOT ask for \"every detail\" / \"the complete text\" / \"an\n112\texhaustive extraction\": a whole document dragged into your context is the one thing you must not\n113\tdo. It is expensive, it crowds out everything else, and it does NOT survive to your next statement\n114\t— **your variables do not persist between statements**, so the giant string you just bound is gone\n115\tnext turn and you will be left re-inspecting a value you cannot name (`Cannot find name '...'`),\n116\tdisplaying counts and fragments instead of talking to the user.\n117\t\n118\tYou do not need the full contents anyway: whoever actually stores the data reads the file\n119\tthemselves. When the material is destined for the project's data, hand the **attachment id** to\n120\tthe automator (path 4a) and let IT read the file in full — that is what `attachmentIds` is for.\n121\tCarry a summary; pass the id.\n122\t\n123\t**Never show them your plumbing.** Everything a specialist, a writer or a fork hands back is\n124\taddressed to YOU, not to the user. Variable names, types, string lengths, ids, row counts of things\n125\tthey never asked to count, raw JSON, \"what we got back\" — that is debugging output. Rendering it is\n126\tnot transparency; it is showing a person the inside of a machine they did not ask to look inside,\n127\tand it tells them nothing about their own material. The test is simple: **would this line mean\n128\tanything to someone who has never seen the code?** If it names a variable, a type, or a byte count,\n129\tthe answer is no. Say what you LEARNED about their material — the things they would recognise as\n130\ttheirs — and keep how you learned it to yourself.\n131\t\n132\tThis is NOT a reason to postpone the reply. \"Don't dump the value\" means *write prose out of it*, in\n133\tthe SAME statement, while you still hold it — not \"hold it for later\". There is no later: your\n134\tvariables do not survive to the next statement."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cfe78b6a-97f2-4499-9269-8aedfbe3c777","uuid":"65143ae9-b13e-41a4-a825-605edd453fcf","timestamp":"2026-07-15T20:50:28.602Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md","content":"Call it once — not every turn — and don't ask the user for a name:\n\n```typescript\nawait setSessionMeta({ title: 'Bolognese from scratch', slug: 'bolognese-from-scratch' });\n```\n\nThe host slugifies `slug` (lowercased, non-alphanumerics → `-`); either field is optional.\n\n## Attachments — you cannot see images/files yourself\n\nYou are a text model: you CANNOT read an attached image or file directly. When your\nmessage lists attachments (each with an `attachmentId`), delegate to the right\nspecialist and pass the id(s), then use the returned text to answer the user. Send ALL\nimage ids in ONE vision delegation and ALL file ids in ONE files delegation (the\